claim.claim-text:
1. A method of polishing a substrate, comprising: 
chemical mechanical polishing a first layer of substrate with a first polishing fluid, the substrate having a second layer disposed under the first layer, the first and second layers having differing reflectivity; 
optically monitoring the substrate during polishing with the first polishing slurry to generate plurality of intensity traces, with each intensity trace including intensity measurements from a different radial range on the substrate; 
once any of the intensity traces indicates an initial clearance of the first layer, chemical mechanical polishing the substrate with a second polishing fluid having different polishing properties than the first polishing fluid; 
continuing to optically monitor the substrate during polishing with the second polishing slurry; and 
halting polishing after all the intensity traces indicate that the second layer has been completely exposed.

12. A method of polishing a substrate, comprising: 
bringing a surface of a substrate into contact with a polishing surface that has a window, the substrate having a first layer disposed over a second layer, the first and second layers having differing reflectivity; 
supplying a first slurry to the substrate for a first polishing step; 
causing relative motion between the substrate and the polishing surface; 
directing a light beam through the window, the motion of the polishing surface relative to the substrate causing the light beam to move in a path across the substrate; 
monitoring a reflectance signal produced by the light beam reflecting off the substrate; 
extracting a plurality of intensity measurements from the reflectance signal; 
generating a plurality of intensity traces, with each intensity trace including intensity measurements from a different radial range on the substrate; and 
supplying a second slurry to the substrate for a polishing second polishing step when any of the intensity traces indicates an initial clearance of the first layer, the second slurry having different polishing properties than the first slurry; and 
halting polishing after all the intensity traces indicate that the second layer has been completely exposed.

14. A method of polishing a substrate having a metal layer disposed over an oxide layer, comprising: 
bringing a surface of a substrate into contact with a polishing surface that has a window; 
supplying high-selectivity slurry to the polishing surface; 
causing relative motion between the substrate and the polishing surface; 
directing a light beam through the window, the motion of the polishing surface relative to the substrate causing the light beam to move in a path across the substrate; 
monitoring a reflectance signal produced by the light beam reflecting off the substrate; 
extracting a plurality of intensity measurements from the reflectance signal; 
determining a radial position for each intensity measurement; 
dividing the plurality of intensity measurements into a plurality of radial ranges according to the radial positions; 
generating a plurality of intensity traces, with each intensity trace including intensity measurements from one of the plurality of radial ranges; 
supplying low-selectivity slurry to the polishing surface when any of the intensity traces indicates an initial clearance of the metal layer; and 
halting polishing when all the intensity traces indicate that the oxide layer has been completely exposed.
